comments.body:
@zhangguanzhang: it's actually hard to respond to requests when people are complaining about individual word sets once the PR is squashed. OTOH, if they complain about a word family and it's still in its component parts, then dropping them is trivial.

Since you aren't going to merge the PR as is at this point, there's really no reason for me to squash it eagerly. It's already cost me time on a few iterations.

As I said above, I'm happy to squash at the end when people are no longer complaining about the actual changes.

@rhatdan: sorry about the `vendor`ed stuff. I usually work w/ a filter that protects from changing `vendor`ed bits:
https://github.com/jsoref/podman/blob/spell-check/.github/actions/spelling/excludes.txt#L10
I probably didn't have it applied (since it isn't part of the PR, it's the extra branch `spell-check` or merge `spelling-with-spell-check`) and I was switching to one of the other repositories. As to not having `codecleanup` catch things. If you like this cleanup, the [action](https://github.com/marketplace/actions/check-spelling) can try to enforce this to protect against future regression.

re: `-ful`/`-full`, I don't really care which way to go (as a native speaker, I do agree that `-ful` should be preferable if it's acceptable, but as a potential contributor, I'll go whichever way the project will let me). I do agree that it should be as consistent as possible, some divergence leads to more divergence.

wrt "everywhere", is there anything else I can do to help? I can apply changes to other public repositories. (This set of PRs -- `buildah`, `podman`, and `skopeo` was added to my queue collectively.) -- Thankfully w/ my tooling, it's just `rs rootfull rootful` which is a really easy thing to do -- although, it's also not much harder for me to create a full spelling PR.

@edsantiago: https://github.com/containers/podman/pull/8787/commits/7315615c1c94c5089c7dab47fecb3cc2f63aa38a is the current commit for this jitter.
